12 Other verbs
The same plan is shared by all margin verbs.

sales |&gt;
  union_all_with_margins(
    .grouping = rollup(region, store)
  )

# A tibble: 15 × 6
   region store  year product channel amount
   &lt;chr&gt;  &lt;chr&gt; &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt;   &lt;chr&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
 1 East   E1     2024 A       Online      10
 2 East   E1     2025 A       Store       12
 3 East   E2     2024 B       Store       20
 4 East   Total  2024 A       Online      10
 5 East   Total  2024 B       Store       20
 6 East   Total  2025 A       Store       12
 7 Total  Total  2024 A       Online      10
 8 Total  Total  2024 B       Store       20
 9 Total  Total  2024 A       Online      15
10 Total  Total  2025 A       Store       12
11 Total  Total  2025 &lt;NA&gt;    Online      18
12 West   Total  2024 A       Online      15
13 West   Total  2025 &lt;NA&gt;    Online      18
14 West   W1     2024 A       Online      15
15 West   W1     2025 &lt;NA&gt;    Online      18

sales |&gt;
  nest_with_margins(
    .grouping = rollup(region, store)
  )

# A tibble: 6 × 3
  region store data            
  &lt;chr&gt;  &lt;chr&gt; &lt;list&gt;          
1 East   E1    &lt;tibble [2 × 4]&gt;
2 East   E2    &lt;tibble [1 × 4]&gt;
3 East   Total &lt;tibble [3 × 4]&gt;
4 Total  Total &lt;tibble [5 × 4]&gt;
5 West   Total &lt;tibble [2 × 4]&gt;
6 West   W1    &lt;tibble [2 × 4]&gt;

sales |&gt;
  nest_by_with_margins(
    .grouping = rollup(region, store)
  )

# A tibble: 6 × 3
# Rowwise:  region, store
  region store data            
  &lt;chr&gt;  &lt;chr&gt; &lt;list&gt;          
1 East   E1    &lt;tibble [2 × 4]&gt;
2 East   E2    &lt;tibble [1 × 4]&gt;
3 East   Total &lt;tibble [3 × 4]&gt;
4 Total  Total &lt;tibble [5 × 4]&gt;
5 West   Total &lt;tibble [2 × 4]&gt;
6 West   W1    &lt;tibble [2 × 4]&gt;


union_all_with_margins() emits one input-row copy per grouping set. nest_with_margins() returns an ordinary nested result, while nest_by_with_margins() returns its row-wise counterpart. The summarize and union verbs support local and lazy tables; the two nesting verbs support local data frames and dtplyr steps because their results contain list columns.
